{
  "text": "We turn to the second generalization of R due to to Garsia and Haiman. First we need to define a generalization of the Vandermonde product (4) to two sets of variables. Let µ ⊢ n. Coordinatize the squares of the diagram of µ by letting (i − 1, j − 1) be the coordinate of the square in the ith row and jth column. For instance, the coordinates of the squares of the diagram of µ = (3, 2) are given by 0,0 0,1 0,2 1,0 1,1 j 1 ) , . . . , (i n , j n ) be the coordinates of the squares of the diagram of µ (in some order), and define the n × n determinant The n! conjecture of Garsia and Haiman [CITATION_1] [13], later proved by Haiman [CITATION_2] , is the following assertion.",
  "correct_citation": {
